<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I could parade about 100 sites on the internet that provide backing, and documentation for what a scumbag Kerry is, but it isn't relevent to the debate, that was my argument.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I don't think whether or not Bush/Kerry are scumbags matters, I think all politicians have personal skeletons in the closet.  Bush's Iraq policy was wrong, and is failing- Abu Ghraib demonstrates how other policy failures have taken place.  That is what I've been arguing.<br>
<br>
As far as his NG service goes- I think the issue isn't whether or not he served his country, I think the question is wealth and privelage.  The fact is that some poor kid from NY or mississippi wouldn't have managed to secure the privelaged treatment he did.  There is enough evidence that privelage was wrongfully used that I have lost respect for Bush as a person.<br>
<br>
Just to be clear though, I don't think personality has jack shit to do with the issues.  That's why I was shocked what a big deal people made out of the whole Lewinsky thing- neither Bush using privelage to escape military service/having been a drunkard, or Clinton getting a sexual favor from an intern directly affects policy issues to any great degree.  If Bush hadn't abandoned containment then invaded Iraq or withdrawn from almost 20 international treaties, some of them significant changes of US policy going back 50 years- then I'd probably think of his administration a lot differently.  The policies have made America and the world a more dangerous place.<br>
<br>
You don't have to take my word for it, the International Institute of Strategic Studies report has directly linked the Iraq war to a significant rise in terrorism.  No one's disputed this, or argued this.  More to the point, I don't think anyone on this forum thinks that Guantanomo bay or Abu Ghraib have helped to defeat terrorism so much as inflaming support for it.  <br>
<br>
I wish people would stand up and condemn a wrongful policy they way they used to.  I remember after Iran/Contra how senior Republicans constructively criticized the policy and related policies and how Reagan took responsibility for it and brought Congress together to enact protections against it happening again.  That is a lasting legacy of leadership that remains to this day.  Bush claims to be following in Reagan's footsteps.  He should start acting like it.<br>
<br>
